fields.value: Price and Control Elasticities of Demand for Savings

dsDescriptionValue.value: A Philippine bank tested sensitivity to interest rates and account ownership requirements in 10,000 randomized door-to-door solicitations for a commitment savings account. Take-up is substantial (23%), but price elasticity of saving in this account is not significantly different from zero in either the full sample or sub-groups of plausibly marginal savers. The upper bound is less than 0.5 in the full sample, and exceeds 1.0 in only 1 of 22 sub-groups. Nor do we find sensitivity to ownership requirements.

fields.value: Research Support, Innovations for Poverty Action

otherGeographicCoverage.value: Rural and peri-urban areas near Dipolog, Pagadian, Iligan

value: People living in the catchment area of First Valley Bank who had an adult present and willing to talk to a marketer at the time of the visit.

fields.value: Administrative data from First Valley Bank in the Philippines; Surveys with marketers from First Valley Bank

First Valley Bank marketers traveled to all villages within the catchment area of the bank and went door-to-door, speaking to 10,000 households. They surveyed all households with someone present and willing to speak to a marketer. They first administered a survey on savings. Once the survey was complete, marketers used a PDA application to randomize people into low, high, or reward interest rate accounts, and into individual accounts, joint accounts (if there was a couple present), or a choice of joint or individual accounts. People then chose whether to open an account.
In-person interviews; bank administrative data on accounts
